  <entry>
    <title>Modeling Pair Distribution Functions Using DISCUC</title>
    <link href="https://www.huaecho.cn/Tools/DISCUC/4072560629.html"/>
    <id>https://www.huaecho.cn/Tools/DISCUC/4072560629.html</id>
    <published>2023-08-07T15:35:27.000Z</published>
    <updated>2023-08-07T15:35:27.000Z</updated>
    
    
    <summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/DISCUC/Cover/DiffuseCodeNano.jpg?imageMogr2/format/avif&quot; alt=&quot;DISCUC&quot; title=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;50%&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;DISCUS is a comprehensive program designed to generate disordered
atomic structures and compute corresponding experimental data, such as
&lt;strong&gt;single crystal diffuse scattering&lt;/strong&gt; or the &lt;strong&gt;atomic
pair distribution function (PDF)&lt;/strong&gt;. Key features include
&lt;em&gt;symmetry operations&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Monte Carlo simulation
capabilities&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;the ability to generate domain
structures&lt;/em&gt;, among others. More recent developments in DISCUS have
expanded its functionality to include the simulation of
nanoparticles.&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
    
    
    
