  <entry>
    <title>Principles of Resonant inelastic X-ray Scattering</title>
    <link href="https://www.huaecho.cn/uncategorized/ea3abef5.html"/>
    <id>https://www.huaecho.cn/uncategorized/ea3abef5.html</id>
    <published>2022-12-02T17:16:24.000Z</published>
    <updated>2022-12-04T03:25:30.000Z</updated>
    
    
    <summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://oss.huaecho.cn/blogimage/RIXSPrinciple/Cover/RIXSCover.jpg?imageMogr2/format/avif&quot; alt=&quot;Principles of Resonant inelastic X-ray Scattering&quot; title=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;50%&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;X-ray Resonant Inelastic Scattering&lt;/em&gt; (&lt;em&gt;RIXS&lt;/em&gt;) is an
emerging excitation spectroscopy technique developed over the past
decade. Leveraging the coupling of photons with the majority of degrees
of freedom that determine material properties—including lattice, charge,
spin, and orbitals—RIXS spectra can observe various excitations such as
phonons, magnons, orbitons, and electronic level transitions, thereby
providing rich physical information. Additionally, RIXS inherits the
advantages of X-ray techniques, allowing its application in the
measurement of low-dimensional materials and small samples. These
benefits have positioned RIXS technology as a valuable tool in fields
such as condensed matter physics, materials science, chemistry, and
biology.&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
    
    
    
    
  </entry>
  
